Here's a simple example of a Discord bot using Discord.js v14 which includes a "ban" slash command:

```javascript
const { Client, Intents, CommandInteraction } = require('discord.js');
const client = new Client({ intents: [Intents.FLAGS.Guilds] });

client.once('ready', async () => {
    console.log('Bot is ready!');

    // Define a ban command
    let banCommand = {
        name: 'ban',
        description: 'Bans a user',
        options: [{
            name: 'user',
            type: 'USER',
            description: 'The user to ban',
            required: true,
        }],
    };

    // Register the ban command to the guild
    const guild = client.guilds.cache.get('YOUR_GUILD_ID');
    await guild.commands.create(banCommand);
});

client.on('interactionCreate', async (interaction) => {
    if (!interaction.isCommand()) return;

    const { commandName } = interaction;

    if (commandName === 'ban') {
        if (!interaction.member.permissions.has('BAN_MEMBERS')) {
            return await interaction.reply('You do not have permission to use this command.');
        }

        const user = interaction.options.getUser('user');
        if (user) {
            const member = interaction.guild.members.resolve(user);
            if (member) {
                await member.ban();
                await interaction.reply({ content: `User ${user.tag} was banned.`, ephemeral: true });
            }
        }
    }
});

client.login('YOUR_BOT_TOKEN');
```

Replace 'YOUR_GUILD_ID' and 'YOUR_BOT_TOKEN' with your actual Discord guild ID and bot token, respectively. This bot will ban the user specified in the "ban" slash command if the command user has "Ban Members" permission.

Here's a basic example of a C++ function that could convert a markdown-formatted string to an html-formatted string. It is important to note that markdown can be quite complex and this function only handles headers and paragraphs:

```cpp
#include <regex>
#include <string>

std::string markdownToHTML(std::string& md) {
    std::string html = md;

    // Convert headers
    std::regex headerPattern("^(#{1,6}) (.*)$");
    std::smatch match;
    while (std::regex_search(html, match, headerPattern)) {
        int level = match.str(1).length();
        html.replace(match.position(), match.length(), "<h" + std::to_string(level) + ">" + match.str(2) + "</h" + std::to_string(level) + ">");
    }

    // Convert paragraphs
    std::regex paragraphPattern("^(?!<h.*>$)(.*)$");
    while (std::regex_search(html, match, paragraphPattern)) {
        html.replace(match.position(), match.length(), "<p>" + match.str(1) + "</p>");
    }

    return html;
}
```

This function uses regular expressions to search for markdown syntax in the input string and replace it with the corresponding HTML syntax. Headers are defined in markdown by beginning a line with one to six '#' characters, followed by a space and the header text. Paragraphs are simply lines of text that are not headers.

This is a very basic implementation and doesn't handle many of the other features of markdown, such as links, images, lists, and more. For a full markdown to HTML converter, you might want to use a library such as `cmark`, the official C implementation of CommonMark.

